Chapter 4. Multivariate Data¶

  • Multivariate data can be summarized and viewed in ways that are similar to those discussed for bivariate and univariate data
  • Looking at all the variables simultaneously, or holding some variables constant while looking at others are the two ways to handle multiple variables.

4.1 Viewing multivariate data¶

Three-way contingency tables(n-way contingency tables)
It shows relationships among three (or n) variables using tables.

Let's investigate whether paying for a cable modem affects the relationship between having a cell phone and a car. Use a three-way table.

In [4]:
# Paying for a cable modem requires cutbacks elsewhere.
# table() function uses the first two variables for the main tables
# and the remaining variables to construct different tables for each combination
# of the variables.

table(cell.phone, car, cable.modem)

, , cable.modem = N

          car
cell.phone N Y
         N 1 2
         Y 2 3

, , cable.modem = Y

          car
cell.phone N Y
         N 0 0
         Y 1 1

Flattened contingency tables

The tables are set side-by-side, with the column headings layered to indicate the levels of the conditioning factor.

The layout represented in table 4.2 can be achieved with the ftable() function. Call it on the result of a table() command

In [5]:
# not side-by-side
ftable(table(cell.phone, car, cable.modem))

               cable.modem N Y
cell.phone car                
N          N               1 0
           Y               2 0
Y          N               2 1
           Y               3 1

Specify the desired row variables or column variables.

The column variables are set with the argument col.vars=.

This argument expects a vector of variable names or indices.

In [8]:
ftable(table(cell.phone, car, cable.modem), col.vars = c("cable.modem", "car"))

           cable.modem N   Y

cell.phone

Y                      2 3 1 1

4.1.3 Comparing relationships¶

Scatterplots(): used to investigate relationships between two variables.
They can also be used when there are more than two variables.

Use different plot characters or colors to distinguish the variables in order to plot multiple relationships on the same scatterplot.

babies(UsingR)
Several variables collected from new mothers as part of a study on child health and development.
The variables include gestation period, maternal age, whether and how much the mother smokes, and other factors, such as mother's level of education.

A built-in function for creating scatterplots of all possible pairs of variables : pairs()

  • The plot of gestation versus weight
In [30]:
attach(babies)
gestation[gestation == 999] <- NA
plot(gestation, wt, main = "Scatterplot of gestation\nversus weight by smoke factor(Unspecified)")
# A different plot
plot(gestation, wt, pch=smoke, main = "Scatterplot of gestation\nversus weight by smoke factor")
legend(170, 170, legend=c("never", "yes", "until pregnant", "long ago", "unknown"), pch=c(0:3,9))

The smoke variable has five "factors" or "categories": "0", "1", "2", "3", "9"

If we want to use consequent indices for colors (e.g. 1,2,3,4,5 for five categories) in using the function rainbow()...

Currently, the factors are not continuous. So we change "9" to "4" to make the five "categories" form an increasing sequence.

smoke[smoke == 9] <- 4

4.2 R basics: data frames and lists¶

Multivariate data consists of multiple data vectors considered as a whole.

Combining all those separate variables into a single data object has many advantages.

These "objects" are usually DATA FRAMES in R.

A data frame is used to store rectangular grids of data.

  • Each row: measurements on the same subject, statistical unit, or experimental unit.
  • Each column: a data vector containing data for one of the variables.

The collection of entries need not all be of the same type, but each column must contain the same type of entry as they are data vectors!!!.

A rectangular collection of values, all of the same type, may also be stored in a matrix.

List
A more general type of storage than a data frame. Think of a list as a collection of components. Each component can be any R object, such as a vector, a data frame, a function, or even another list.

A data frame is a list with top-level components given by equal-length data vectors.

In [121]:
x <- 1:2
# y = c("a", "b")
y <- letters[1:2]
z <- 1:3
dt1 <- data.frame(x,y)

# Error, the top-level components are not equal in length.
data.frame(x,y,z)

A list is a very flexible type of data object. Many of the functions in R, such as lm(), have return values that are lists.

Lists can be used to store variables of different lengths.

In [125]:
ls1 <- list(x,y,z)

    1. 1

    1. 'a'
    2. 'b'

[[1]] says this is for the first toplevel component of the list, which is a data vector.

The following [1] refers to the first entry of this data vector.

One difference that isn’t apparent in the output, when using data.frame to create a data frame, is that character variables, such as y, are coerced to be factors, unless insulated with I.

Adding names to a data frame or list

Just like data vectors, both data frames and lists can have a names attribute. These are found and set by the names() function or when we define the object. The names of a list refer to the top-level components.

For data frames, these top-level components are the variables. In the above examples, the command data.frame(x,y) assigns names of x and y automatically, but the list() function does not. If we want to define names when using data.frame() or list() we can use a name=value format, as in

In [131]:
list(x.name=x, "y name" = y)
$x.name
  1. 1
  2. 2
$`y name`
  1. 'a'
  2. 'b'

The names() function can be used to retrieve or assign the names. When assigning names it is used on the left side of the assignment (when using the equals sign). For example:

In [132]:
eg <- data.frame(x,y)
# See the current variable names
names(eg)
  1. 'x'
  2. 'y'
In [134]:
# Change the names with the same function, names()
# Does not return anything
names(eg) <- c("x.name", "y name")

# Check the changed names. 
# names() returns the variable names of the 'eg' data frame.
names(eg)
  1. 'x.name'
  2. 'y name'

Data frames can also have their column names accessed with the function colnames() and their rows named with rownames(). Both can be set at the same time with dimnames(). The row names must be unique, and it is recommended that column names be also. These functions are applicable to matrix-like objects.

In [135]:
eg
x.namey name
1a
2b
In [136]:
# See the current column names of the data frame 'eg'.
colnames(eg)
  1. 'x.name'
  2. 'y name'
In [137]:
# change names again with the same function, colnames()
colnames(eg) <- c("hi", "there")

# Check the changed names.
colnames(eg)
  1. 'hi'
  2. 'there'
In [138]:
# You can also check and change the names of rows with rownames()
# If no specific names are assigned, numbers are assigned as default names.
rownames(eg)
  1. '1'
  2. '2'
In [139]:
# Let's change row names
rownames(eg) <- c("What's", "Your name?")
rownames(eg)
  1. 'What\'s'
  2. 'Your name?'

The size of a data frame or list

Data frames represent a number of variables, each with the same number of entries. The ewr (UsingR) is an example. As this data is matrix-like, its size is determined by the number of rows and columns. The dim() function returns the size of matrix-like objects:

In [142]:
# number of rows, number of columns; the return value is a data vector.
dim(ewr)
str(dim(ewr))
  1. 46
  2. 11
 int [1:2] 46 11
In [143]:
# Therefore, you can access the second value separately by an index
dim(ewr)[2]
11

Row and column sizes may also be found directly with nrow() and ncol().

In [144]:
# the number of rows
nrow(ewr)

# the number of columns
ncol(ewr)
46
11

A list need not be rectangular. Its size is defined by the number of top-level components in it. This is found with the function length(). As data frames are lists whose top-level components are data vectors, the length of a data frame is the number of variables it contains.

In [145]:
# number of top-level components, or the "variables" of the data frame ewr.
length(ewr)
11

4.2.2 Accessing values in a data frame¶

Accessing variables in a data frame by name

When R attaches a data frame it makes a copy of the variables. If we make changes to the variables, the data frame is not actually changed. This results in two variables with the same names but different values.

In [1]:
x <- data.frame(a=1:2, b=3:4)
# You cannot find a outside the data frame, 'x'
a

Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): 객체 'a'를 찾을 수 없습니다
Traceback:
In [2]:
attach(x)
# This is the copy of the variable 'a' in the data frame 'x'
a
  1. 1
  2. 2
In [3]:
# Change a value of the copy.
a[1] <- 5
a
  1. 5
  2. 2
In [4]:
# However, the original data frmae 'x' does not change in its values
x
ab
13
24
In [5]:
detach(x)
# An object 'a', previously copied from the variable 'a' of the data frame 'x'
# remains in the global environment
a
  1. 5
  2. 2
In [6]:
# x is still not changed.
x
ab
13
24

Accessing a data frame using [,] notation

When we use a spreadsheet, we refer to the cell entries by their column names and rows number. Data-frame entries can be referred to by their column names (or numbers) and/or their row names (or numbers).

Entries of a data vector are accessed with the [] notation. This allows us to specify the entries we want by their indices or names. If df is the data frame, the basic notation is df[row, column]

There are two positions to put values, though we may leave them blank on purpose. In particular, the value of row can be a single number (to access that row), a vector of numbers (to access those rows), a single name or vector of names (to match the row names), a logical vector of the appropriate length, or left blank to match all the rows.

Similarly for the value of column. As with data vectors, rows and columns begin numbering at 1.

In [7]:
df <- data.frame(x=1:3, y=4:6)
rownames(df) <- c("row 1", "row 2", "row 3")
df
xy
row 114
row 225
row 336
In [8]:
# The entry of the third row, second column = 6
df[3,2]
6
In [9]:
# This will yield the same result as above
df["row 3", "y"]
6
In [10]:
# rows 1, 2, and 3
df[1:3, 1]
  1. 1
  2. 2
  3. 3
In [12]:
# rows 1 and 2, columns 1 and 2
df[1:2, 1:2]

# rows 1 and 3, columns 1 and 2
df[c(1,3), 1:2]
xy
row 114
row 225
xy
row 114
row 336
In [13]:
# all rows, column 1 = returns vector
df[,1]
  1. 1
  2. 2
  3. 3
In [14]:
# a vector of logical values can be used as well.
# The length of the vector should be equal to the number of rows, or columns
# depending on which dimension you use the vector to refer to.
df[c(F,T,F), ]
xy
row 225

age[age==99] <- NA

In [25]:
# 'remove' the copies
rm(gestation);rm(age);rm(inc)
detach(babies); attach(babies)

# Guess what the values stored in the variable, 'not.these' would represent.
# '|' means 'OR', a logical operator
not.these = (gestation==999) | (age == 99) | (inc == 98)

# Make a new data frame. '!' is another logical operator, 'NOT'.
tmp <- babies[!not.these, c("gestation", "age", "wt", "inc")]

# Now you can see the scatterplots with gestation = 999, age = 99, inc = 98
# removed
pairs(tmp)
detach(babies)
In [31]:
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
options(repr.plot.height = 4)

# Access with logical vectors
attach(ewr)

# columns 3 through 10 are for the airlines

# This will plot the rows with the values of the variable "inorout" equal to "in"
# R will compare if a value of the variable "inorout" in every row is "in".
# If the result of the comparison is "TRUE", that row will be selected
# If the result of the comparison is "FALSE", that row will not be selected.
# Only the selected rows will be plotted
boxplot(ewr[inorout == "in", 3:10], main = "Taxi in")

# This will plot the rows with the values of the variable "inorout" equal to 'out'
boxplot(ewr[inorout == "out", 3:10], main = "Taxi out")
detach(ewr)

The argument to boxplot() is a data frame (=boxplot) and not a data vector (such as boxplot$inorout).

If the first argument to boxplot() is a list, then each component is plotted with separate boxplots. As a data frame is a list, this behavior makes using boxplot() much easier than typing in all the variable names. When a boxplot is called with a list, any names for the list are used to label the boxplot.

The subset() function An alternate to using using the [,] notation to extract values from a data frame is to use the subset() function:

new.df=subset (old.df, subset=…, select=…)

subset= -> use a logical condition to restrict the rows used

select= -> use a vector of the desired variable names or indices to restrict the columns

When we use subset (), the variable names are searched within the data frame. There is no need to attach the data frame or use with ().

The previous examples could have been completed as follows:

In [36]:
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
options(repr.plot.height = 4)

# The argument 'subset=' uses a vector of logical values.
# inorout=="in" will return TRUE for the entries "in" and FALSE for "out"
ewr.in <- subset(ewr, subset=inorout=="in", select=3:10)
ewr.out <- subset(ewr, subset=inorout=="out", select=3:10)
boxplot(ewr.in, main="Taxi in")
boxplot(ewr.out, main="Taxi out")

How can we sort a data frame by one of its columns and have the other columns reflect this new order?

-> sort() will not work.

-> order() is the one to use.

order(x) returns the indices of the sorted values of x, a data vector, so x[order(x)] will be x sorted from smallest to largest.

In [34]:
x <- c(3, 2, 10, 4, 29)
# Indices are returned
order(x)

# ordered x; x[order(x)] = x[c(2,1,4,3,5)]
# Thus, it will return the second, the first, the fourth, the third, 
# and the fifth value of x consequently.
x[order(x)]
  1. 2
  2. 1
  3. 4
  4. 3
  5. 5
  1. 2
  2. 3
  3. 4
  4. 10
  5. 29

Accessing a list

List access using [[]] : [[]] is used to access list components

In [43]:
lst <- list(a=1:2, b=letters[1:3], c=FALSE)

# The return value = 1
lst[[1]]

# The name of a component can be used
lst[['a']]

# This is not 2, but c('a', 'b', 'c')
lst[[2]]
  1. 1
  2. 2
  1. 1
  2. 2
  1. 'a'
  2. 'b'
  3. 'c'

The $ notation

In [49]:
lst <- list(one.to.two = 1:2, "a-e" = letters[1:5])
lst$one.to.two

# unique shortening = R will match names even if they are not exactly the same.
# It will match, as long as we use enough letters to identify that name
# 'uniquely' among the possible names
lst$o

# When the name includes blanks or other special characters, it needs to be
# quoted
lst$"a-e"
  1. 1
  2. 2
  1. 1
  2. 2
  1. 'a'
  2. 'b'
  3. 'c'
  4. 'd'
  5. 'e'

4.3.3 Creating contingency tables with xtabs()¶

If we have the count data, not the raw data, we can enter the data in as a data frame and then use xtabs() to create contingency tables.

as.data.frame() inverts what xtabs() and table() do.

In [123]:
percents <- c(71, 70, 79, 82, 71, 83, 71, 50, 70, 71, 55, 73)
car <- rep(c("passenger", "pickup", "van/suv"),4)
year <- rep(rep(2001:2002, c(3,3)),2)
enforcement <- rep(c("primary", "secondary"),c(6,6))
seatbelts <- data.frame(percents, car, year, enforcement)
seatbelts

# xtabs() creates contingency tables using a model-formula interface.
# first two components to make a table, the third component to break up the tables

tab <- xtabs(percents~car+year+enforcement, data=seatbelts)

4.3.4 Manipulating data frames: split() and stack()¶

split(): split up a variable by the levels of some factor.

e.g) boxplot(split(x,f)) produces the same results as boxplot(x~f)

tapply(x,f,function) will do the same thing.

stack() is inverse to split(). It takes a collection of variables stored in a data frame or list and stacks them into two variables. One contains the values, and the other indicates which variable the data originally came from

4.4 Lattice graphics¶

The basic idea is that the graphic consists of a number of panels. Each panel corresponds to some value(s) of a conditioning variable. The lattice graphing functions are called using the model-formula interface. The formulas have the format

response ~ predictor|condition

In [130]:
library(lattice)
# trellis.device(bg="white") : No longer available
options(lattice.theme = "col.whitebg")
In [131]:
# The argument type="density" makes the total area of the histogram add to 1
# This is the same as prob=TRUE argument in hist()
histogram(~wt|factor(smoke), data=babies, subset = wt!=999, type="density")
In [132]:
densityplot(~wt|factor(smoke), data=babies)
In [133]:

bwplot(gestation~factor(inc), data=babies, subset=gestation!=999)

bwplot(gestation~factor(inc)|factor(smoke, labels=c("never","yes",'until pregnant','long ago','unknown'))
       , data=babies, subset=gestation!=999&inc!=98)

xyplot(wt~gestation|factor(smoke), data=babies, subset=(wt!=999&gestation!=999))

# Scatterplots with regression line

plot.regression <- function(x,y)
    {
    panel.xyplot(x,y)
    panel.abline(lm(y~x), lty=2, col="red")
}

xyplot(wt~gestation | factor(smoke), data=babies, 
       subset=(wt != 999 & gestation != 999), panel=plot.regression)

# However, first coercing a data vector to a factor,
# THEN setting the values of the level of that factor different from the
# values of the factor could be done with levels()
# However, this will transform the original values of the factor with respect to
# the values of the level defined by a user.
x <- factor(1:3)
# levels are equivalent to the values of the factor, x
levels(x)
# change the levels to c("a", "b", "c")
levels(x) <- letters[1:3]
# the values of the factor, x, are now transformed into "a", "b", and "c",
# so to be alinged with the levels.
x
